⁰ Aristotle does not recognise this account of matter as understood in every parc proposition, but only as aamercort in a erodat. (See above, p. 46.) In the latter case it is no test of quantity, as there are universal and particular propositions of each mode. The distinction in the text, however, seems to have been early introduced. It is implied in the commentary of Ammonius on de Int. 7. (Scholia, p. 115. a 14.) And Petrus Hispanus defines the three kinds of matter thus: nweaay, when the predicate is of the essencc, or a property: σοπιίηρσηε, when it is an accident to the subject: impossible, when a repugnant quality. In this point of view, the sup- posed criterion of quantity is inapplicable to propositions in which the predicate is an inseparable accident. But the whole question of matter is clearly extra-logical. See Sir W. Hamilton, Discussions, p. 148, The Lopiciart cannot determine a proposition to be necessary or contingent, unless stated as such. The point must be ascertained from the Science to which the proposition materially belongs. The Logician, however, may use indefinitas as particulare, not assigning a quantity from the matter, but admitting an indefinite premise (and therefore conclusion) where the rules of the figure do not require an universal. Hence the minor premise in fig. l. may be indefinite, but not the major. See An. Pr. i. 4. 9.
